{{Infobox Patriarch | image = Rahmani1.jpg | honorific-prefix = Mar | name = Ignatius Ephrem II Rahmani | birth_name = Ephrem Rahmani | church = [[Syriac Catholic Church]] | see = [[Patriarch of Antioch]] | patriarch_of = [[List of Syriac Catholic Patriarchs of Antioch|Patriarch of Antioch]] | residence = [[Beirut]] | enthroned = 9 October 1898 | ended = 7 May 1929 | predecessor = [[Ignatius Behnam II Benni]] | successor = [[Ignatius Gabriel I Tappuni]] | birth_date = 21 November 1848 | birth_place = [[Mosul]], [[Iraq]] | death_date = {{BirthDeathAge||1848|11|21|1929|5|7|yes}} | death_place = [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] | ordination = April 1873 ([[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|Priest]]) | consecration = 2 Oct 1887 ([[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Bishop]]) | consecrated_by = [[Ignatius George V Shelhot|George V Shelhot]] }}
Mar '''Ignatius Dionysius Ephrem II Rahmani''' (21 November 1848 &ndash; 7 May 1929) was [[Patriarch]] of the [[Syriac Catholic Church]] from 1898 to 1929 and a [[Syriac language|Syriac]] scholar.
==Life== Ephrem Rahmani was born on 21 November 1848<ref name="CH">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/brahm.html|title=Archbishop Ignacio Dionisio Efrem Rahmani (Rahamani)|publisher=Catholic-Hierarchy|accessdate=2009-03-01}}</ref> (or on 9 November 1849 according to other sources<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriaccatholic.org/Rahmany.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193148/http://www.syriaccatholic.org/Rahmany.aspx|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2016-03-03|title=البطريرك أغناطيوس أفرام الثاني رحماني|accessdate=2009-03-01}} </ref>) in [[Mosul]]. He studied by the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friars in Mosul and later in the [[College of the Propaganda]] in [[Rome]] and was ordained priest in April 1873.
Rahmani was appointed vicar of the bishop of Mosul with the [[Titular see|titular]] title of bishop of [[Edessa, Mesopotamia|Edessa]] and consecrated bishop on 2 October 1887 by Patriarch [[Ignatius George V Shelhot]]. On 1 May 1894 Rahmani was appointed bishop of [[Aleppo]]. After the death of [[Ignatius Behnam II Benni]] (13 September 1897) he was elected Patriarch on 9 October 1898 and confirmed by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 28 November 1898.
As patriarch Rahmani was particularly interested in the instruction of the clergy. The early 20th-century was a period of expansion for the [[Syriac Catholic Church]] who received many [[Syrian Orhtodox Church|Syriac Orthodox]] converts.<ref name="King">{{cite book|pages=75–76|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9g6BTkcwXWMC&pg=PA84#PPA75,M1|title=The Rites of Eastern Christendom|isbn=978-1-59333-391-1|first=Archdale |last=King|origyear=1947/8|year=1997}}</ref> In 1910{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} he moved the [[Episcopal See|Patriarchal See]] from [[Mardin]] to [[Beirut]].
With the [[World War I]] arrived the catastrophe: the [[Armenian Genocide]] brought destruction also to the Christian Syrians who lived in the same areas of the Armenians, and the Syriac Catholic Church had the number of its members cut by half<ref name="Frazee">{{cite book|last=Frazee| first=Charles A. |title=Catholics and Sultans: The Church and the Ottoman Empire 1453&ndash;1923 |year=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-02700-7 |pages=295 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X6DM4szwUpEC&printsec=frontcover#PPA295,M1 |accessdate=2009-02-25}}</ref> with five dioceses (on ten) and fifteen missions destroyed.
Ephrem Rahmani died in [[Cairo]] on 7 May 1929.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/anti1.htm|title=Patriarchal See of Antioch|publisher=GCatholic.org|accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref>
==Works== Ephrem Rahmani was a liturgical scholar of international repute.<ref name="King"/> In 1899 he discovered and published the first edition of the 4th-century text ''[[Testamentum Domini]]''. His main contribution on the history of the liturgy is his book ''Les Liturgies Orientales et Occidentales'', Beyrouth, 1929
